accesses.lakeAccessComments: Access is for ATV and carry down only.  Very tight switchback at the end of the trail near the water.

surveys.narrative:
Franklin Lake is a 135 acre, class 13 lake, located approximately six miles northwest of Crane Lake, Minnesota. Franklin Lake is mostly shallow. The carry-in access located on the south side of the lake was used during the survey.

Northern pike gill-net abundance was 12.0 fish/set, which was well above most class 13 lakes. Five year-classes were present and age ranged from 1-5 years. Total length ranged from 15.9-25.1 inches. Growth and average weight were below average.

The walleye population greatly exceeded most class 13 lakes. Giill-net abundance was 24.5 fish/set. Typically 75% of class 13 lakes are below 10.5 fish/set. Sixteen year-classes were present and age ranged from 1-18 years. Total length in gill nets ranged from 9.5-23.6 inches and the average was 17.4. Length at age-4 was 16.7 inches, which was 2 inches more than the average for the International Falls Management Area. Average weight of walleyes captured in gill nets was also above average.

Yellow perch gill-net abundance was 25.2 fish/set, which was well above what is normally observed in class 13 lakes. Six year-classes were present and age ranged from 2-8 years. Total length ranged from 5.6-11.9 inches. Growth was above the area average.

WALLEYE GILLNET CPUE INCREASED FROM 7.5 FISH/SET IN 1973 TO 10.5 FISH/SET. THE MEAN SIZE OF WALLEYE DECREASED FROM 1.9 LBS IN 1973 TO 1.5 LBS. IN 1989 ALL AGE-CLASSES FROM 1 TO 8 WERE REPRESENTED IN THE GILLNET CATCH. WALLEYE MN GILLNET PSD WAS 75, AN INCREASE FROM 63 IN 1973; THIS INCREASE WAS THE RESULT OF NO STRONG RECENT YEAR-CLASSES IN THE CATCH. NORTHERN PIKE INDEX OF ABUNDANCE ALSO INCREASED; GILLNET CPUE 4.5 FISH/SET IN 1973 TO 10.00 FISH/SET IN 1989. YELLOW PERCH INDEX OF ABUNDANCE DECREASED FROM 67.0 FISH/SET IN 1973 TO 16.5 FISH/SET. PERCH AVERAGE LENGTH DECREASED WHICH IS REFLECTED IN THE PSD DECREASE . NORTHERN PIKE AND YELLOW PERCH CATCHES WERE WITHIN THE QUARTILE RANGED DEVELOPED. THE WALLEYE CATCH WAS ABOVE THE 3RD QUARTILE FOR LAKES IN THIS CLASS SUGGESTING A HIGH POPULATION.

There is a high density population of small to medium sized northern pike in Franklin Lake. Over three times the lake class average number of northerns were sampled. Average size sampled was 19.4 inches and 1.8 pounds. The largest northern pike sampled was 28.3 inches. Walleye were sampled in average to high numbers for this lake type. Average size was 18.0 inches and 2.0 pounds. The largest walleye sampled was 25.2 inches. Natural reproduction appeared to be sufficient and consistent. Yellow perch were sampled at a level almost three times the average for this lake type. Average length sampled was 7.0 inches, and the largest perch sampled was 10.5 inches. Growth for all species was similar to that in other Minnesota lakes. Reproduction for all species appeared consistent, and adequate.

Franklin Lake is a shallow 156 acre lake located approximately 10 miles east of Crane Lake. Access to Franklin is carry-in or ATV only. Check with the US Forest Service to be sure the trail is currently open to ATV before making the trip. For those who make the effort to access the lake, Franklin should provide ample angling opportunities. Northern Pike are abundant, with an average length of 20 inches, and fish up to 31.9 inches sampled. Walleye are naturally reproducing and well above average in numbers for similar lakes. They also average over 16 inches and 1.5 pounds. Yellow Perch are fast growing and fairly abundant with fish up to 10.9 inches sampled.
Walleyes were first introduced to this lake (500,000 fry) in 1958.

Franklin is a small, fairly shallow, ATV accessed lake located 10 miles east of Crane Lake, MN. Walleye, northern pike and yellow perch dominate the fish community. The 1999 population assessment found walleye numbers remaining high with the average fish measuring 17.0 inches and weighing 1.7 pounds. Walleyes up to 10 years old and 27.0 inches in length were found during this investigation. Good numbers of northern pike were also present, although average length was only 19.2 inches and average weight was 1.7 pounds. There was an occasional pike over 30 inches sampled in 1999. High numbers of yellow perch were sampled with an average length of 8.5 inches and a range from 5.7 to 12.5 inches. One additional forage species, white sucker, was also documented.

Franklin Lake is a shallow 156 acre lake located approximately 10 miles east of Crane Lake. Access to Franklin is carry-in or ATV only. Check with the US Forest Service to be sure the trail is currently open to ATV before making the trip. Walleye are naturally reproducing and well above average in numbers for similar lakes, and are over 18 inches in length and just shy of 2 pounds on average. Northern Pike are abundant, with an average length of 20 inches, and fish up to 31.5 inches sampled. For those who make the effort to access the lake, Franklin should provide ample angling opportunities.
